This show was part of the Summer Camp Music Festival. During the rain delay, the band played a second acoustic set in the crowd. Kurt & Pete were on unplugged guitars, Trev on his unplugged bass, Ben on djembe, and JonL on cowbell. After music was stopped during the first set, the weather was so bad for so long that Goose would not have gotten to get back on stage if it wasn't for lespecial, Brass Against, and the Summer Camp Staff at the Soulshine tent for coming up with a new schedule, which cut time from their sets, but allowed all three bands to play music. Huge thanks to everyone involved!!

data.jamchart_notes: Monster AIN w/ multiple amazing movements. Pete opens things with incredible synth work, but Spuds is the real star; driving this monster jam towards a magnificent melodic peak! Some very funky playing from Richk closes this all-timer.

The Buffalo Arcadia: An iconic fan favourite. Rick's bright rhythm playing spurs Peter into an uplifting bliss segment early on, which leads to several minutes of sustained soloing. Seemingly ends and then gets revived by the band for another extended run around pure euphoria before returning home. Recommended for a sunny afternoon.
Short, pretty jam that finishes with a wonderful return to the Indian River riff.

data.jamchart_notes: A twisting “fast Need” with a danceable exploratory initial jam that pivots over a drum break into a more dynamic guitar-led section. As Rick passes the baton to Trevor, they descend into an almost marching section with a syncopated drum line and thumping bassline. Rick finds a new melody that the band quickly backs as a looping hook that naturally summons the composed tail.

data.jamchart_notes: Might as well call this “Tremble,” with the entirety of the jam built on Trevor’s thumping bass line. After an unusually fast-paced composed head, the two-section improv begins with Rick exploring morphing loops before dropping into a slightly twangy almost southern rock jam.

data.jamchart_notes: Efficient Pete-led 14-minute journey initiated by his vibesy accompaniment as Rick arpeggiates out of the head section. A soaring synth jam that starts bright and clean morphs into a grittier sawtoothy lead section before landing them into a floating full-band jam with sort of “Scarlet”-islandy motif undergirded by rolling drum fills and well-placed Trevor flair. Rick leads out from there with a punchy attack that twists the tropical theme into a short but assertive closing statement.
